ğŸ“Œ C++ programming mein, operators, variables aur constants ke saath, data ko manipulate karne ke liye use hoti hai. Operators, variable ko manipulate karne ke liye use hoti hai.

ğŸ“Œ C++ programming mein, operators ke kuch types hain. Yeh hain:

ğŸ“ 1: Arithmetic Operators: Yeh operators, arithmetic calculations ke liye use hai. Yeh hain: + (addition), - (subtraction), * (multiplication), / (division), % (modulus).

ğŸ¯ğŸ¯ğŸ¯ExampleğŸ¯ğŸ¯ğŸ¯:

#include <iostream>
int main() {
    int a = 10;
    int b = 20;
    int c;

    c = a + b;
    std::cout << "Addition: " << c << std::endl;
    c = a - b;
    std::cout << "Subtraction: " << c << std::endl;
    c = a * b;
    std::cout << "Multiplication: " << c << std::endl;
    c = a / b;
    std::cout << "Division: " << c << std::endl;
    c = a % b;
    std::cout << "Modulus: " << c << std::endl;
    return 0;
}

ğŸ“Œ Is example mein, arithmetic operators ke saath, arithmetic calculations ke liye use kiya gaya hai.

ğŸ“ 2: Relational Operators: Yeh operators, data ko compare karne ke liye use hai. Yeh hain: == (equal to), != (not equal to), < (less than), > (greater than), <= (less than or equal to), >= (greater than or equal to).

ğŸ¯ğŸ¯ğŸ¯ExampleğŸ¯ğŸ¯ğŸ¯:

#include <iostream>
int main() {
    int a = 10;
    int b = 20;
    int c;

    c = (a == b);
    std::cout << "Equal to: " << c << std::endl;
    c = (a != b);
    std::cout << "Not equal to: " << c << std::endl;
    c = (a < b);
    std::cout << "Less than: " << c << std::endl;
    c = (a > b);
    std::cout << "Greater than: " << c << std::endl;
    c = (a <= b);
    std::cout << "Less than or equal to: " << c << std::endl;
    c = (a >= b);
    std::cout << "Greater than or equal to: " << c << std::endl;
    return 0;
}

ğŸ“Œ Is example mein, relational operators ke saath, data ko compare kiya gaya hai.

ğŸ“ 3: Logical Operators: Yeh operators, data ko logical AND, OR aur NOT karne ke liye use hai. Yeh hain: && (logical AND), || (logical OR), ! (logical NOT).

ğŸ¯ğŸ¯ğŸ¯ExampleğŸ¯ğŸ¯ğŸ¯:

#include <iostream>
int main() {
    int a = 10;
    int b = 20;
    int c;

    c = (a < b) && (a == 10);
    std::cout << "Logical AND: " << c << std::endl;
    c = (a < b) || (a == 20);
    std::cout << "Logical OR: " << c << std::endl;
    c = !(a < b);
    std::cout << "Logical NOT: " << c << std::endl;
    return 0;
}

ğŸ“Œ Is example mein, logical operators ke saath, data ko logical AND, OR aur NOT kar diya gaya hai.

ğŸ“ 4: Assignment Operators: Yeh operators, variable ko initialize aur assign karne ke liye use hai. Yeh hain: = (assignment), += (addition assignment), -= (subtraction assignment), *= (multiplication assignment), /= (division assignment), %= (modulus assignment).

ğŸ¯ğŸ¯ğŸ¯ExampleğŸ¯ğŸ¯ğŸ¯:

#include <iostream>
int main() {
    int a = 10;
    int b = 20;
    int c;

    c = a;
    std::cout << "Assignment: " << c << std::endl;
    c += a;
    std::cout << "Addition assignment: " << c << std::endl;
    c -= a;
    std::cout << "Subtraction assignment: " << c << std::endl;
    c *= a;
    std::cout << "Multiplication assignment: " << c << std::endl;
    c /= a;
    std::cout << "Division assignment: " << c << std::endl;
    c %= a;
    std::cout << "Modulus assignment: " << c << std::endl;
    return 0;
}

ğŸ“Œ Is example mein, assignment operators ke saath, variable ko initialize aur assign kiya gaya hai.


ğŸ“Œ Note: C++ programming mein, operators ke saath, variables aur constants ke saath, data ko manipulate kar sakte hai. Operators, variable ko manipulate karne ke liye use hoti hai.

ğŸ“Œ C++ programming mein, strings, character sequences hai jo ek saath use hoti hai. C++ programming mein, strings, double quotes ke saath define karte hai.

ğŸ“Œ C++ programming mein, strings, built-in library ke part hai jo string ki nokri karne ke liye use hoti hai. Is library mein, strings ke saath kaam karne ke liye, functions hai jo ek saath use hoti hai.

ğŸ“Œ C++ programming mein, strings ko declare karne ke liye, aapko double quotes ke saath define karna hoga. Initialize karne ke baad, aapko strings ko use kar sakte hai.

ğŸ¯ğŸ¯ğŸ¯ExampleğŸ¯ğŸ¯ğŸ¯:

#include <iostream>
#include <string>

int main() {
    std::string str = "Hello World!"; // declare a string
    std::cout << str << std::endl; // print the string

    return 0;
}

ğŸ“Œ Is example mein, double quotes ke saath, string declare kiya gaya hai aur usme "Hello World!" value assign kiya gaya hai. Phir, std::cout ke saath, string ko print kiya gaya hai.

ğŸ“Œ C++ programming mein, strings ko declare karne ke baad, aapko strings ko use kar sakte hai. Use karne ke baad, aapko strings ko manipulate kar sakte hai.

ğŸ“Œ C++ programming mein, strings ke saath, built-in library ke functions ke saath, strings ko manipulate kar sakte hai. Yeh functions hai:

ğŸ“ 1: length(): Yeh function, string ki length return karti hai.

ğŸ¯ğŸ¯ğŸ¯ExampleğŸ¯ğŸ¯ğŸ¯:

#include <iostream>
#include <string>

int main() {
    std::string str = "Hello World!"; // declare a string
    int len = str.length(); // get the length of the string
    std::cout << "Length of the string: " << len << std::endl;

    return 0;
}

ğŸ“Œ Is example mein, ".length()" function ka use karke, string ki length print ki gai hai.

ğŸ“ 2: substr(): Yeh function, string ki ek part ko return karti hai. Yeh function, starting index aur length ke saath, string ki ek part ko return karti hai.

ğŸ¯ğŸ¯ğŸ¯ExampleğŸ¯ğŸ¯ğŸ¯:

#include <iostream>
#include <string>

int main() {
    std::string str = "Hello World!"; // declare a string
    std::string sub = str.substr(0, 5); // get a substring
    std::cout << "Substring: " << sub << std::endl;

    return 0;
}

ğŸ“Œ Is example mein, ".substr(0, 5)" function ka use karke, "Hello" value ko substring ke roop mein print kiya gaya hai.

ğŸ“ 3: find(): Yeh function, ek substring ko string mein find karti hai. Yeh function, substring aur starting index ke saath, substring ko string mein find karti hai.

ğŸ¯ğŸ¯ğŸ¯ExampleğŸ¯ğŸ¯ğŸ¯:

#include <iostream>
#include <string>

int main() {
    std::string str = "Hello World!"; // declare a string
    int pos = str.find("World"); // find the position of "World"
    std::cout << "Position of World: " << pos << std::endl;

    return 0;
}

ğŸ“Œ Is example mein, ".find("World")" function ka use karke, "World" value ko string mein find kiya gaya hai aur uska index print kiya gaya hai.C++ programming mein, strings ko declare karne ke baad, aapko strings ko use kar sakte hai. Use karne ke baad, aapko strings ko manipulate kar sakte hai aur built-in library ke functions ke saath, strings ko manipulate kar sakte hai.

